      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1121">
               <p>Ingham, a native of <placeName>Ossett, Yorkshire</placeName>, matriculated at
                     <placeName>Queen&apos;s College, Oxford</placeName> in <date when="1730"
                     >1730</date>, and in <date>1733</date> became involved with the Wesley brothers
                  in the &apos;Oxford Methodists&apos;. He received his <seg ana="degree">BA</seg>
                  in <date when="1734">1734</date>, was ordained in <date when="1735-06">June
                     1735</date>, and accompanied <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> and <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"
                     />CW</persName> to minister in <placeName>Georgia</placeName>. Thus, he met the
                  Moravians on the ship going to <placeName>Georgia</placeName>. When Ingham
                  returned to <placeName>England</placeName> he accompanied <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> in <date when="1738"
                     >1738</date> to <placeName>Herrnhut</placeName> and
                     <placeName>Marienborn</placeName>. Ingham&apos;s initial labors in the
                  evangelical revival that was breaking out were focused in the West Riding of
                  Yorkshire. As the Wesley brothers and Moravians parted ways in the early
                     <date>1740s</date>, Ingham sided with the Moravians. In <date when="1741"
                     >1741</date>, in spite of opposition in her family, Ingham married Lady
                     <persName>Margaret Hastings</persName> (<date from="1700" to="1768"
                     >1700–1768</date>). This helped provide the means to buy Bank House, near
                     <placeName>Pudsey</placeName>, which in <date when="1746-05">May 1746</date>
                  was dedicated as the Moravian headquarters in the north of
                     <placeName>England</placeName>. About a decade later, Ingham separated from the
                  Moravians, leading about 80 congregations into a connexion of
                  &apos;Ighamites&apos; that he guided. See <hi rend="italic">Alumni
                  Oxonienses</hi>; <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 590–91; <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>;
                  Tyerman, <hi rend="italic">Oxford Methodists</hi>, 57–154; and Vickers, <hi
                     rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 175.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
